        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> We could allow something like import cython cython = cython.in_version(\">=3.0\") It would be ignored in compiled code (or maybe fail the build if the Cython version is older), but could do something more or less smart in Python.\r\n\r\nThis might be hard for type-checkers to see through (I think this is the point that Matus is making).\r\n\r\nI think maybe the simplest option is to bundle version specific modules and allow:\r\n\r\n```\r\nimport cython.cython_3_1 as cython\r\n# or\r\nimport cython.cython_3_1  # for user's that want to type it out in full each time\r\n```\r\n\r\n`import cython` just gets the latest version as it does now.\r\n\r\nAt compile-time it's either ignored, or just checked as a warning/error.\r\n\r\nThat way:\r\n* We always recommend users install the latest Cython runtime package.\r\n* If needed, they can use a specific import as a \"pin\" that should work with any future runtime package.\r\n\r\nI'm not sure specifying version ranges is actually more useful than just an exact version.",
